class="comment-text"><p>You do realize that a Mac Pro isn&#8217;t a standard consumer product? I doubt anyone spending that kind of money is concerned about the OS Xs resistance to PC viruses.</p></div><div
class="reply"> <a
class='comment-reply-link' href='/blog/pc-vs-mac/?replytocom=23700#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-23700", "23700", "respond", "42254")'>Reply</a></div></div><div
class="after-comment"><div></div></div></div></li></li></ul></li><li
id="comment-23672" ><div
class="comment-content"><div
class="before-comment"></div><div
class="comment"> <img
alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/76080d9f4ed7f8c22bf7c273198c0385?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /><cite>Brian</cite> Says: <br
/> <small
class="commentmetadata"><a
href="#comment-23672" title="">June 14th, 2011 at 11:16 am</a> </small><div
class="comment-text"><p>Actually neither Mac nor GNU/Linux technically run on top of Unix. They use a unix-like file structure, and most of the console commands work exactly like their Unix counterparts, but they are all actually written to emulate Unix. BSD is the only Operating System that is strictly an extension of Unix.</p><p>@nels: As Tech-Seeker said, Linux would largely eliminate the threat of viruses, while being potentially more efficient than Mac OS (and certainly more versatile and customizable). Not to mention, even on Windows, there are plenty of free Anti-Virus/Malware applications available for Windows which work as well as any paid-for counterpart. (Avast!, Kaspersky, AVG, Malwarebytes, etc)</p><p>Additionally, there ARE indeed viruses for Mac OS (and Linux), and there will only ever be more as long as Mac gains popularity. While Mac OS is definitely more secure than Windows thanks to its Unix-like user permissions and process handling, it is still entirely possible for malicious software to make use of an exploit. Part of the reason Mac OS has been largely immune to viruses/malware is due to there being so few Macs that devoting time to writing malware for them just wasn&#8217;t worth the time.</p><p>Back to the original topic &#8211; indeed similar Apple hardware will cost several times what PC hardware will. Additionally, you&#8217;ll pay an arm and a leg to have your Apple fixed if it&#8217;s no longer on warranty, or you&#8217;ll void your warranty by performing even simple fixes yourself. Mac hardware is in no way better than PC hardware. If you strictly want Mac OS, it is available for Intel PC-compatible processor architectures, so there&#8217;s no excuse for spending several thousand dollars out of your way for, in essence, nothing more than a glossy white case.</p><p>In my experience, Windows 7 has been a perfectly acceptable operating system for general use and especially gaming. When I need a C development environment, I dual-boot into Linux, or use my notebook which is strictly Linux-only. As far as Mac OS is concerned, I have tried several versions, and all I can say is that it&#8217;s very pretty. Windows 7 and Linux with the latest versions of Gnome and KDE have just as much or more eyecandy however, so Mac is no longer superior in that department.</p><p>In the end, I personally can&#8217;t think of a single valid reason why anyone would choose a Mac. The Operating System is solid, sure, but no more so than a properly configured Linux setup. The hardware is stable, sure, but no more so than quality PC hardware which is literally half the price or less. The applications run smoothly, sure, but the same can be said for well-coded applications on Windows or Linux. The white glossy cases are pretty, sure, but you can build a PC that looks like anything you want, and then run Windows, Linux, *or* MacOS on it.</p><p>These are my personal opinions, of course.</p></div><div
