href="#comment-23701" title="">June 15th, 2011 at 5:06 am</a> </small><div
class="comment-text"><p>You completely missed my point. I said there was no 8 core Pentium. Which there isn&#8217;t! The Pentium is Intel&#8217;s budget consumer line. The 8 core Xeons are completely different.</p><p>The Mac server hardware means a hell of a lot in terms of cost. There is no desktop motherboard that supports more than 1 CPU. Go look up the cost for server hardware. I can guarantee you it&#8217;s not going to be anywhere near the $1400 the PC is listed for above. My point was that this is comparing apples to oranges.</p><p>The RAM is special. ECC RAM is much more expensive because it has error checking and correction features that desktop RAM doesn&#8217;t. Not at any point did I mention speed. Not to mention ECC RAM isn&#8217;t compatible on standard desktop motherboards. That&#8217;s why they all say &#8220;non-ECC memory supported&#8221;.</p><p>I didn&#8217;t at any point mention overclocking either, and 99% of people couldn&#8217;t care less about it. A desktop CPU (eg Core i3/5/7, Pentium etc) isn&#8217;t designed to run 24/7. A server CPU will run at the same speed as it&#8217;s desktop equivalent at a much lower voltage. So that extends the life of the CPU and decreases heat and power consumption.</p><p>Yes, a standard desktop HDD will be much cheaper than what Apple provides. And I agree that the upgrade prices from Apple are ridiculous. However, that $1400 PC probably won&#8217;t have anything but the cheapest 1.5TB drive around.</p><p>You don&#8217;t have to use the Apple keyboard and mouse, and keyboard and mouse is compatible. And I use bluetooth quite often. Syncing between phone and computer, phone to phone, file transfer etc. Just because you don&#8217;t use it doesn&#8217;t make it invalid.</p><p>Find me an IPS display with the same resolution and size for less. Please. If you find one I would love to buy it.</p></div><div
