id="comment-23679" style="margin-left: 60px"><div
class="comment-content"><div
class="before-comment"></div><div
class="comment"> <img
alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/43fcd0ddb816877d58a99a0e740eb147?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /><cite>Ethan</cite> Says: <br
/> <small
class="commentmetadata"><a
href="#comment-23679" title="">June 14th, 2011 at 1:16 pm</a> </small><div
class="comment-text"><p>There is no making up of acronyms here. ECC RAM and Server CPUs (like Intel Xeons) are designed to run in servers 24 hours a day. ECC RAM has specific error checking and correction that adds to the stability of the machine. Because of this they are much more expensive than standard desktop memory.</p><p><a
href="http://www.tech-faq.com/ecc-memory.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.tech-faq.com/ecc-memory.html</a></p><p>A server CPU such as a Xeon allows multiple CPUs to run on 1 motherboard. Hence the dual CPU option on the Mac Pro. The architecture is identical to their desktop counterparts, however they are specially selected for running at much lower voltages, therefore putting out much less heat, and consuming much less power. The DIY PC that this article mentions cannot have that feature. At least not for anything close to the price mentioned. Not to mention the server motherboards support much more RAM than a standard desktop PC. Server motherboards also support more connections for other peripherals like HDDs, Fiber cards, etc.</p><p>Only an uneducated fool would make the above picture. Or believe it for that matter. I also wouldn&#8217;t put much faith in a tech blog that posts such drivel.</p></div><div
