class="comment-text"><p>So you are saying you are fine losing customization so that your computer is more stable and easy to use?<br
/> While that&#8217;s a bad idea in my book, you are free to prefer less options so that things are easier for you. HOWEVER, this trade shouldn&#8217;t cost extra money. It should be &#8216;buy the 100 dollar car that you can customize any why you want but will only last two years&#8217; or &#8216;buy the 100 car that you can&#8217;t modify but will last five years&#8217;.<br
/> However in this case, the car cost five times more&#8230; for less options but increased longevity&#8230;<br
/> Considering how fast computers are outdated, by the time you PC is down, it&#8217;s time to buy a new one anyway. With the Mac you have to use it long past it&#8217;s &#8216;up-to-date&#8217; period to justify it&#8217;s price meaning you lose out in the long run.<br
/> In other terms&#8230; You can buy a new PC every other year to stay up to date or buy a mac every five years and be out of date. (Should you buy the next Mac so that you are up-to-date earlier, you lose a lot of money.)<br
/> In math terms&#8230;<br
/> Let&#8217;s say the PC above will last 2 years and the Mac will last 5.<br
/> For the PC, that&#8217;s 7,000 a year. (And saying it will only last 2 years is being nice)<br
/> For the Mac, that&#8217;s 14,600 a year. You could buy a new PC every year for that price&#8230;<br
/> Even if it lasted TEN years, you are at 7,300 a year. By that time you are way behind current technology and still paying more per year than you did with the PC.<br
/> But hey&#8230; at least you didn&#8217;t have to worry about customizing anything. Fight the ones trying to give you more options!</p></div><div
