/> <small
class="commentmetadata"><a
href="#comment-23862" title="">June 29th, 2011 at 6:51 pm</a> </small><div
class="comment-text"><p>The following is only a personal opinion, and I am not a computer science major, nor an economics major.</p><p>I feel there will always be a market for Macs and PCs, or like counterparts. Macs are overpriced because there&#8217;s a market of individuals who value what it means to be &#8216;an apple user,&#8217; as it comes with a certain amount of social prestige, and will pay much more for the name as long as they know their product will work. There will always be a market for PCs where there are people who don&#8217;t mind building their own computer or don&#8217;t mind the extra, even nominal, amount of work it would require to make a computing machine perfect for their needs at a lower cost. The former will always enrage the latter, and the former will always be defensive of their stance.</p><p>And, of course, people will continue to argue their side.</p></div><div
