id="comment-24166" ><div
class="comment-content"><div
class="before-comment"></div><div
class="comment"> <img
alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/5805ec2ed854ff39e6e0269b788cad38?s=32&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /><cite>redjujube</cite> Says: <br
/> <small
class="commentmetadata"><a
href="#comment-24166" title="">August 7th, 2011 at 2:04 am</a> </small><div
class="comment-text"><p>I can afford to have 3 Macs if I wanted them but I didn&#8217;t become well off by squandering my money.  I&#8217;m well off because I&#8217;m thrifty.  I have 7 PCs here that run 24/7, 365 days a year.  They run BOINC which means they run full out crunching numbers all the time and the results of the crunching is verified accurate by other computers crunching the same job.  My oldest is a Pentium 2 and it&#8217;s still using the same HD it started out with.  It and all my other PCs have non-ECC RAM and they very rarely throw compute errors. Do I need to spend that much extra for a Mac for reliability and durability?  Hogwash!  By running BOINC 24/7 and 365, I put my standard PCs through the toughest torture test you can conceive of and they do just fine.  ECC RAM was worth it back in the day when chips were not so radiation resistant and power supplies had more ripple but it serves no purpose today.</p><p>Do I need a dual CPU mobo?  If I wanted one I would have one for a lot less money than a Mac mobo and I could stick the same Xeons in it that Macs have but for less money.</p><p>I don&#8217;t waste my money on that piece of crap Windows either.  I used OS/2 for years and when that OS just wasn&#8217;t viable anymore I switched to Linux and have never regretted it.  My newest PC on Linux can do anything a Mac or Windows machine can do including cloud computing, syncing my phone, etc. It plays Flash, reads and writes PDF, serves up my website, handles Word documents and Excel files, plays MP3 and DVD video and would play Windows Media too if I bought the software for $20 but I don&#8217;t need it. My wireless keyboard and mouse are just as good as anything  Mac has to offer.  I don&#8217;t have Firewire 800 but USB 2.0 is plenty fast enough for me.</p><p>My Nvidia GTX 570 is fully supported including CUDA for crunching BOINC tasks.  All my hardware including WiFi and sound is recognized and fully functional.  All drives including floppy and USB drives are automatically mounted/unmounted. I can use any file system Windows can use. And guess what&#8230; it&#8217;s all FREE.</p><p>Now even if Macs were more durable than a PC (and they aren&#8217;t) I still wouldn&#8217;t get one because all modern electronics is/are so reliable these days it becomes obsolete before it wears out.  All you need to do is use a good quality surge protector and clean them out once in a while to keep them running cool. Oh, I find I need to replace fans once in a while but Macs use the same fans so they don&#8217;t an advantage there.</p><p>If you&#8217;re a Mac fan you&#8217;re a sucker.  That&#8217;s all there is to it.</p></div><div
